{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd5c1b7f-65fe-4dee-95d9-eaa8f9b97fc1","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports via **ReportCrash**. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Check these locations:**\n\n1. **User-level crash reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level crash reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nLook for files named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` or `.crash`.\n\n**To get a core dump instead**, run your app with:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n./YourApp\n```\nCore files typically land in `/cores/`. You can then inspect with `lldb`:\n```bash\nlldb ./YourApp -c /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\n**Tip:** You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** for a GUI view of all collected reports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"27e8e8f4-df51-4142-b3ce-90786d7fad08","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tool calls needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system generates crash reports automatically via ReportCrash. These are stored in specific directories.","outputTokens":309,"requestId":"9812:DE08:7B38BD2:87DD42C:69F40649"},"id":"d9e4bec3-d8f6-4c78-83a2-33a49d9eb793","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:48:00.867Z","parentId":"fe491a76-204a-4f54-9d36-11b7ff5a9c9d"}
